This one is for our FL Studio gang! ⁣
⁣
This stock FL Studio plugin lets you see which notes are being played in complicated audio material. It doesn’t work on everything, but it can be very helpful in studying chords, vocals, and other tonal samples!⁣
⁣
Also helpful for figuring out the key of your samples!⁣
⁣
If this one helps, share with an FL Studio friend!⁣

node.text:
🚨 Using studio monitors? Keep these in mind!
⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
Obviously we don’t all have the luxury of working in a studio, or a perfectly built + treated room. In these instances, there are still a few things we can try and do to improve how we hear our sound.⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
1️⃣ try to create an equilateral triangle between you and your speakers. The distance from Left Speaker to Right Speaker should also be the same distance from your listening position to each speaker. Your speakers should also be angled...not facing straight out!⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
2️⃣ If possible, center your desk in the center of the room. ⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
3️⃣ Try to leave space between the back of your desk / monitors and the wall.⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
4️⃣ Position your speakers facing the long side of the room.⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
5️⃣ Monitors should be EAR level...Not above, not below! If you have a two-tier desk this is fine. In this case, it helps to rest them on foam so they aren't touching the desk. You can also use monitor stands to get the speakers at the exact height needed.⁣⁣⁣
⁣
Of course, there are extra steps you can take to acoustically treat your room...hopefully these are things you can implement today! ⁣⁣⁣
Found this helpful? Smash the like button!! ⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣

This is VERY ⭐️ IMPORTANT to understand! ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Building off our earlier post…be mindful of WHERE you use EQ. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Just because you used one at the beginning of your processing chain, doesn’t mean it’s going keep things the same if you add more processing afterwards.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Your signal flows through the processing chain in a specific order (ableton left to right, logic and FL top to bottom).⁣⁣
⁣⁣
As you add more plugins, they change that signal. With a tool like EQ, it’s okay to use multiple if necessary! ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
You might shape a sound first, then run it through a plugin like saturation/distortion which once again change the frequencies on that signal. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Don’t be afraid to bust out another EQ to get your signal sounding how you want or need. ⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Listen to the example in this video to fully understand this topic! ⁣⁣

node.text:
👀 Let's look at SIX common EQ MISTAKES!
⁣⁣
⁣
SWIPE THROUGH THE POST TO READ MORE ON EACH...⁣
⁣
⁣⁣
⁣
1️⃣ - "WHERE YOU PUT IT"⁣
⁣⁣
2️⃣ - "STUCK IN SOLO"⁣
⁣⁣
3️⃣ - "FIXING ON GROUP / MASTER"⁣
⁣
4️⃣ - "NOT HAVING A PURPOSE"⁣
⁣
5️⃣ - "AFRAID TO PUSH IT"⁣
⁣⁣
6️⃣ - "USING EQ FOR LEVEL / VOLUME"⁣

node.accessibility_caption: 6 bad eq habits when mixing
where you place your equalizer matters.  one may not be enough at the beginning of your chain.  other plugins can add frequencies back to your signal.
use solo mode in your DAW for shaping individual sounds.  not for mixing sounds together.
dont wait til mastering to fix your problems.  when you eq on a master channel or group channel it affects every sound, rather than the one potential sound causing the problem.

mixing is about having intention.  You hear something that needs to be addressed, then you fix it.  Don't just copy EQ settings you saw in a tutorial because you have the same sound.  Every mix is different.
Dont be afraid to push it.  When sound designing its okay to use EQ in ways that may not look correct.  All that matters is how things sound.
Dont use EQ to fix volume issues.  If a sound isn't loud enough, use the volume fader to fix it, not the EQ.  This will save you headroom and improper gain staging as you move into the mixdown.

Tap ❤️ and try this AMAZING vocal reverb trick!

Reverb is an extremely important tool when mixing vocals.

It first allows us to get a more "natural" sound on the recording.

Think about it...everything we hear comes in context of space. Nothing dry sounds "natural" to our ears.

Reverb also allows us to get the vocal to sit better in the mix with its surrounding elements.

One problem with mixing that reverb around the vocal, and into the mix, is that it can take up a lot of time and space (physical + frequency).

If we just slap a reverb on a vocal (insert or send/return) we can run into an issue where the reverb bleeds over the original vocal take (longer decay times). They are happening at same time, and space.

Try sending your vocal to a return channel / bus that has a reverb on it (100% wet).

Then place a compressor after the reverb, and sidechain it back to the original vocal take.

This will duck your reverb whenever the vocal is being performed, and then allow its volume to come back up when the vocal stops.

In most cases, you'd want to do this to create a subtle, more natural sound. Go with a faster attack, fast to medium release (you can shape this by ear) and have the volume duck just a little bit.

If you do too much reduction, the pump of reverb might be too obvious and create more unwanted artifacts.

On the flip-side...from a creative standpoint you can hard pump / sidechain a reverb around a vocal (or even a synth) and achieve some REALLY cool sounds!

Take advantage of this technique and get the best of both worlds...a clean, clear vocal + reverb!
